==English==
===Etymology===
From a cartoon by [[w:George du Maurier|George du Maurier]] published in ''[[w:Punch (magazine)|Punch]]'' magazine 9 November 1895 titled ''True Humility''.  A [[curate]] is having breakfast at his [[bishop]]'s house,
: Bishop: "I'm afraid you've got a bad egg, Mr Jones."
: Curate (not wanting to give offence): "Oh, no, my Lord, I assure you that parts of it are excellent!"
===Noun===
'''[[curate]]'s [[egg]]'''
# (''figuratively'') A thing which has good and bad parts.